   "source": [
    "import pyworld\n",
    "\n",
    "frame_period = 5 # ms\n",
    "hop_length = int(0.001 * fs * frame_period)\n",
    "\n",
    "x = x.astype(np.float64)\n",
    "f0, timeaxis = pyworld.harvest(x, fs, frame_period=frame_period)\n",
    "spectrogram = pyworld.cheaptrick(x, f0, timeaxis, fs)\n",
    "aperiodicity = pyworld.d4c(x, f0, timeaxis, fs)\n",
    "\n",
    "# This trims spectrum that has very small power. Just to make visualization looks good.\n",
    "from nnmnkwii.util import trim_zeros_frames\n",
    "spectrogram = trim_zeros_frames(spectrogram)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Let's see spectrogram representaion\n",
    "librosa.display.specshow(np.log(spectrogram).T, sr=fs, \n",
    "                         hop_length=hop_length, x_axis=\"time\",\n",
    "                         y_axis=\"linear\", cmap=\"magma\")\n",
    "colorbar()"
   ]

    "silence_indices = labels.silence_frame_indices()\n",
    "trimmed_spectrogram = spectrogram[:labels.num_frames()]\n",
    "silence_removed_spectrogram = np.delete(trimmed_spectrogram, silence_indices, axis=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "librosa.display.specshow(np.log(silence_removed_spectrogram).T, sr=fs, \n",
    "                         hop_length=hop_length, x_axis=\"time\",\n",

    "from nnmnkwii.frontend import merlin as fe\n",
    "from nnmnkwii.util import example_question_file\n",
    "\n",
    "binary_dict, continuous_dict = hts.load_question_set(example_question_file())\n",
    "# `add_frame_features` True tells merlin frontend to extract frame-level features\n",
    "linguistic_features = fe.linguistic_features(labels, binary_dict, continuous_dict,\n",
    "                                            add_frame_features=True) \n",
    "# Not so good, but better than text\n",
    "librosa.display.specshow(linguistic_features.T, sr=fs, \n",
    "                         hop_length=hop_length, x_axis=\"time\", cmap=\"magma\")"

    "To load data, you can use our dataset implementations. In this example, we will show how the most basic `FileSourceDataset` works, which loads data on-demand while iteration or indexing."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true

   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from nnmnkwii.datasets import FileSourceDataset\n",
    "\n",
    "X, Y = FileSourceDataset(X), FileSourceDataset(Y)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "### Utterance-wise iteration"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since typically speech features are saved per utterance. It is nartual to support utterance-wise dataset itearation with `FileSourceDataset`. Let's try it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Linguistic feature shape (T, D): (578, 425), Acoustic feature shape (T, D): (578, 187)\n",
      "Linguistic feature shape (T, D): (675, 425), Acoustic feature shape (T, D): (675, 187)\n",
      "Linguistic feature shape (T, D): (606, 425), Acoustic feature shape (T, D): (606, 187)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for (x, y) in zip(X, Y):\n",
    "    print(\"Linguistic feature shape (T, D): {}, Acoustic feature shape (T, D): {}\".format(x.shape, y.shape))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can see time-aligned linguistic/acoustic feature pairs, as we did in the previous section."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Memory cache iteration"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One of the extension of `FileSourceDataset` is that `MemoryCacheDataset`, which has cache functionality."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],

    "X, Y = MemoryCacheDataset(X), MemoryCacheDataset(Y)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "As you can see, after iteration, we have cached utternaces (collected features are stored as is). This is useful when we iterate dataset multiple times. "
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Frame-wise iteration"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The last step of the section shows how to iterate dataset by frame-wise manner. Similar to `MemoryCacheDataset`,  we provide `MemoryCacheFramewiseDataset`. One thing I should note is that we need to give utterance lengths at dataset construction time. This is because by design, a dataset represents *fixed* sized set of features. Without utterance lengths (i.e. number of time frames for each utterance), we cannot compute size of dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from nnmnkwii.util import example_file_data_sources_for_acoustic_model\n",
    "\n",
    "X, Y = example_file_data_sources_for_acoustic_model()\n",
    "X, Y = FileSourceDataset(X), FileSourceDataset(Y)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "[578, 675, 606]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "utt_lengths = [len(x) for x in X]\n",
    "print(utt_lengths)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from nnmnkwii.datasets import MemoryCacheFramewiseDataset\n",
    "\n",
    "X = MemoryCacheFramewiseDataset(X, utt_lengths)\n",
    "Y = MemoryCacheFramewiseDataset(Y, utt_lengths)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
